=3D"margin:0;">On Sunday evening, about 100 hours after <strong>Jeff Bezos =
</strong>set off a
fresh round of hysteria at <em>The</em> <em>Washington Post</em>, several p=
rominent members of the Washington <em>haut monde</em> gathered at the Kenn=
edy Center to honor the legacy of one of his more universally beloved prede=
cessors, the late <strong>Katharine Graham</strong>. The event, which featu=
red a screening of a new documentary about her legendary stewardship of the=
 paper=E2=80=94through <strong>Nixon</strong>, the Pentagon Papers, Waterga=
te, and so on=E2=80=94was hosted by Graham=E2=80=99s old friend
<strong>Warren Buffett </strong>and attended by the likes of <strong>Bill G=
ates</strong>, <strong>David Rubenstein</strong>, <strong>Tony Blinken</str=
ong>, and<strong> Sally Quinn</strong>, the writer and widow of <strong>Ben=
 Bradlee</strong> who has served for decades as Washington=E2=80=99s imperi=
al hostess.<br/><br/><strong>Katie Robertson</strong>, who covered the even=
t for the <em>Times</em>,
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
